     1	---
     2	title: Target Onboarding Guide
     3	description: How to add a new bounded target to deep-improvement without weakening guardrails.
     4	---
     5	
     6	# Target Onboarding Guide
     7	
     8	Workflow for onboarding new deep-improvement targets while keeping evaluator discipline, manifest clarity, and promotion safety intact. Use it when a new target is genuinely needed rather than just interesting.
     9	
    10	---
    11	
    12	## 1. OVERVIEW
    13	
    14	### Purpose
    15	
    16	Explains how to add a bounded target to `deep-improvement` without weakening the existing manifest and benchmark rules.
    17	
    18	### When to Use
    19	
    20	Use this reference when:
    21	- adding a new target profile
    22	- deciding whether a target should be canonical, derived, or candidate-only
    23	- checking whether target growth is still safe
    24	
    25	### Core Principle
    26	
    27	Target growth should be explicit, repeatable, and evaluator-backed. If the target cannot be classified or benchmarked cleanly, it is not ready.
    28	
    29	---
    30	
    31	## 2. PRECONDITIONS
    32	
    33	Only add a target when all of the following are true:
    34	
    35	- the target has a structured output contract
    36	- the target can be benchmarked deterministically or with policy-stable rules
    37	- the target can be classified clearly as canonical, derived, or candidate-only
    38	- the target does not require mirror sync to prove the experiment result
    39	
    40	---
    41	
    42	## 3. REQUIRED STEPS
    43	
    44	1. (Optional) Add the manifest entry in `assets/agent-improvement/target_manifest.jsonc` if the target needs explicit classification or guardrail protections
    45	2. Run `generate-profile.cjs` to derive a scoring profile from the agent's own structure and rules:
    46	
    47	   ```text
    48	   node scripts/agent-improvement/generate-profile.cjs --agent=.opencode/agents/{name}.md
    49	   ```
    50	
    51	3. Run `score-candidate.cjs` against the target for a dynamic-mode 5-dimension baseline
    52	4. Run `run-benchmark.cjs` against packet-local outputs for the new target if benchmark evidence is required
    53	5. Confirm reducer output still separates target families cleanly
    54	
    55	Dynamic mode is the only scoring path. There are no static profiles to maintain.
    56	
    57	---
    58	
    59	## 4. CLASSIFICATION RULES
    60	
    61	- `canonical`: may become promotion-eligible only with explicit guardrails
    62	- `derived`: downstream packaging surface only
    63	- `candidate-only`: benchmarkable and scoreable, but not promotable in the current packet
    64	
    65	---
    66	
    67	## 5. CURRENT RECOMMENDATION
    68	
    69	- every target is onboarded through dynamic mode; there is no static, automatically promotion-eligible profile
    70	- promotion remains a per-target decision requiring explicit operator approval, repeatability evidence, and manifest boundary compliance
    71	
    72	---
    73	
    74	## 6. RELATED RESOURCES
    75	
    76	- `../model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md`
    77	- `../../assets/agent-improvement/target_manifest.jsonc`
    78	

